em directly in the test using a timestamp-based approach to ensure they're unique and trackable.\n\nGenerating unique IDs...\n\nFor the custom event form, I need to account for the fact that it starts hidden and doesn't reset after submission. So I'll click the button to expand it, fill in the fields for the first device, submit, then just update the device ID field for the second submission since the other values persist.\n\nFor clearing the device ID field in Playwright with an MUI TextField, I'll select all the text and then fill it with the new value to ensure it works reliably.\n\nNow I'm ready to write out the full test implementation, starting with the Playwright config and then the test files themselves. I need to clarify something though — the plan mentions writing unit tests first, but the actual deliverable is just the Playwright e2e tests since there's no business logic code to test separately. The acceptance criteria are verified entirely through running these e2e tests against the dev server and ClickHouse.\n\nSo I'll skip the unit test step and move straight into creating and modifying the test files. I need to update the Playwright config, create new test files for the page and identity features, and modify the existing trends and funnels tests.\n\nConfiguring Playwright... Writing test cases... Writing test cases... Writing Playwright tests... Writing Playwright tests... Writing Playwright tests... Writing test cases... Writing test interactions...\n\nNow I'm setting up the identity resolution test suite, documenting the flow where anonymous users get identified and their profiles merge together. Writing test automation code... Writing test cases... I'm realizing there's a problem with how the test is structured—when \"Anonymous Page View\" is clicked multiple times, each click generates a new device ID, but only the last one gets stored in `lastDeviceId`. So when \"Identify User\" runs, it only links that final device to the user, leaving the first