ween what the spec intends and how the code actually behaves. I'm going to write the test using the API directly to verify the spec's actual intent—5 events from a single device attributed to the user after identity resolution—and document this deviation in the handoff.\n\nBut wait, let me reconsider the plan itself. It explicitly says to use the UI and expects ≥5 events, not exactly 5. Since the test might run multiple times and accumulate events for the same user, and the assertion is \"greater than or equal to 5,\" running this test a few times would naturally build up enough events to pass. Each run adds 2 events from the last device used.\n\nThe real problem is the first run would only generate 2 events, failing the assertion. I need to either pre-populate events via the API before running the UI flow, use a unique user per test run to start fresh, or adjust the assertion to match what a single run actually produces. The cleanest approach is probably using a unique identifier per test run and pre-seeding the necessary events through the API first, then running through the UI flow to verify the identity resolution works correctly. I'm going to simplify this and split it into two separate tests: a pure API test for the identity resolution flow that covers BR-101, and a separate UI test for the Testing page interactions. This keeps the tests focused and aligns better with the acceptance criteria. Writing the test structure... Writing test assertions...\n\nNow I'm setting up the second test case to verify that multiple devices linked to the same user both show up in the identity cluster, starting by creating two distinct device IDs and a user email, then sending events to link the first device. Writing test assertions...\n\nActually, I'm realizing the User Profile page is a Server Component that fetches data server-side, so events sent via API should be immediately visible without client-side caching. The ReplacingMergeTree with FINAL should handle deduplication properly, so when we POST an event with device_id and user_id together, the identity mapping should be queryable right away.\n\nI'm a bit concerned about ClickHouse's FINAL modifier potentially being slow on first deduplication, but with just a few test rows it should be fine. There's also a small timing risk between posting events and navigating to the server-rendered profile page, but a full page navigation should give enough time for the data to be available.\n\nFor the test assertion, I need to be more careful with the regex matching the event count. Instead of trying to parse the exact number from the heading text, I should just verify the timeline is visible and then separately check that the events array has the expected length. Profile function to understand the events limit.\n\nLooking at the user profile page, it displays the event count with `Event Timeline ({profile ? profile.events.length : 0} events)`. So for 5 events, I'd expect to match \"Event Timeline (5 events)\" using a case-insensitive regex. The grammar stays consistent regardless of count—it always says \"events\" even for singular values.\n\nNow I need to check the `getUserProfile` function to see what events it returns and whether there's any limit applied.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2099,"cache_read_input_tokens":73778,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2099},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"eb1717ec-5d87-4414-9ed1-88e4656c8afb","uuid":"1f78a98b-d67b-4513-aa72-4b969d564145"}
