{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_014JgvmiYVVWZge8186UkbV6","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t## F13 – getUserProfile null detection for missing users\n2\t\n3\t`min(DateTime64)` in ClickHouse returns the epoch (`1970-01-01 00:00:00.000`) rather than\n4\t`NULL` when the aggregation runs over an empty result set (non-nullable column type).\n5\tChecking `statsRows[0].first_seen === null` would therefore never detect a missing user.\n6\tDecision: include `count() AS event_count` in the stats query and check\n7\t`Number(event_count) === 0` to detect \"no events found\". The unit test was updated to mock\n8\t`{ event_count: 0, first_seen: epoch, ... }` to match this behaviour.\n9\t\n10\t## F2 – TCP vs HTTP port mismatch for `./clickhouse client --port`\n11\t\n12\t`CLICKHOUSE_URL` (e.g. `http://localhost:8123`) uses the HTTP port, but `./clickhouse client`\n13\tconnects via the native TCP protocol whose default port is **9000**, not 8123.\n14\t\n15\t`scripts/migrate.ts` passes whatever port appears in `CLICKHOUSE_URL` to `--port`, so a default\n16\t`CLICKHOUSE_URL` of `http://localhost:8123` will tell the client to connect on TCP port 8123, which\n17\twill fail if ClickHouse is listening on the native TCP port 9000.\n18\t\n19\t**Decision**: keep the current behaviour (pass the URL port as-is) so the env var controls the\n20\tport explicitly. Operators running a non-default setup must set `CLICKHOUSE_URL` to the native TCP\n21\tport (e.g. `http://localhost:9000`) when using `pnpm migrate`. The default local setup with the\n22\tbundled binary uses port 9000 for native TCP — adjust `CLICKHOUSE_URL` or set `--port` separately\n23\tif needed. This is an integration concern; unit tests are not affected.\n24\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"eb1717ec-5d87-4414-9ed1-88e4656c8afb","uuid":"38ec1b4d-040c-4ee1-8e90-99754e54469d","timestamp":"2026-04-15T19:49:04.883Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/riccardocaranfil/bitrefill/minipanel-blank-night-2/ISSUES.md","content":"## F13 – getUserProfile null detection for missing users\n\n`min(DateTime64)` in ClickHouse returns the epoch (`1970-01-01 00:00:00.000`) rather than\n`NULL` when the aggregation runs over an empty result set (non-nullable column type).\nChecking `statsRows[0].first_seen === null` would therefore never detect a missing user.\nDecision: include `count() AS event_count` in the stats query and check\n`Number(event_count) === 0` to detect \"no events found\". The unit test was updated to mock\n`{ event_count: 0, first_seen: epoch, ... }` to match this behaviour.\n\n## F2 – TCP vs HTTP port mismatch for `./clickhouse client --port`\n\n`CLICKHOUSE_URL` (e.g. `http://localhost:8123`) uses the HTTP port, but `./clickhouse client`\nconnects via the native TCP protocol whose default port is **9000**, not 8123.\n\n`scripts/migrate.ts` passes whatever port appears in `CLICKHOUSE_URL` to `--port`, so a default\n`CLICKHOUSE_URL` of `http://localhost:8123` will tell the client to connect on TCP port 8123, which\nwill fail if ClickHouse is listening on the native TCP port 9000.\n\n**Decision**: keep the current behaviour (pass the URL port as-is) so the env var controls the\nport explicitly. Operators running a non-default setup must set `CLICKHOUSE_URL` to the native TCP\nport (e.g. `http://localhost:9000`) when using `pnpm migrate`. The default local setup with the\nbundled binary uses port 9000 for native TCP — adjust `CLICKHOUSE_URL` or set `--port` separately\nif needed. This is an integration concern; unit tests are not affected.\n","numLines":24,"startLine":1,"totalLines":24}}}
